  "response": "The number of stars in the sky is actually impossible to pinpoint precisely. Our own galaxy, the Milky Way, contains an estimated 100-400 billion stars. Beyond the Milky Way, there are billions of other galaxies, each with their own billions of stars. Estimates suggest that the observable universe contains roughly 1 septillion (1,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000) stars, but this number could be even higher as our understanding and observational capabilities improve.",
